730209f-c.title: General view - 8th Avenue - West.
730209f-c.text:
8O Eighth Avenue, at the N.E. corner of West 14th
Street (County Trust Co. Building) general view weatward).
Three views photographed from the above location
towards the North (Hudson) River to show there various
west side docks and ocean liners. These extend from
Tenth anu Eleventh Avenue's, and West Street.
Across the foreground uns the Ninth Avenue Elevated
line crossing 14th ano 1bth Street's (in Views 1 and 2).
View 3 is slightly to the south to shor Gansevoort Street
to the left. At the foot of same appears the group of
buildings corprising west and Washington Market.
May 31, 1930

P. L. Sperr

730208f-a.title: General view - 8th Avenue - Northeast.
730208f-a.text:
80 Eighth Avenue, at the N.E. c rner of West 14th
Street (County Trust Co. Building) general view northeastward.
A set of three views photographed in the direction of
Madison Sqquare and overlooking the zone between 14th and 23rd
Streets. At that point aprear the '~ew York Life and the Metropolitan
Buildings.
Thru the foreground runs Seventh Avenue, and the prominent
New York Telephone Co. Building (No. 206 West 18th Street) is to
the west of same. The side of this structure seen by the viewer
is on West 17th Street.
To the r'ght, and directly on Seventh Avenue are two
tall structures. The first is a 12 story loft building, No.
106-110 Seventh Avenue (oetween 16th and 17th Streets), and
the second, a new 18 story apartment house at the S.W. corner of
West 18th Street. This latter struoture is on the former site
of the 3-story Arnold Constable and Co. stable (92-98 Seventh
Avenue). In the near future another 18 story apartment will separate
these buildings. This will be at the N.W. corner of 16th Street and
abut the aforennentioned loft.
In the distant background appears (view 3) the R. C. A.,
10 East 40th Street, Lincoln, Chanin and Chrysler Buildings.
May 31, 1930
Views 1, 2, 3
P. L. Sperr
NO REPROODUCTIONS
